# LAMMPS Input File
# Licensed under CC BY 4.0
# A Set of Materials-Science Tutorials for the LAMMPS Simulation Package: 2. Materials Science
# By Simon Gravelle, Mark A. Tschopp, Jacob R. Gissinger, and Axel Kohlmeyer
# Tutorial 11: A screw dislocation from its elastic displacement field
#
# Create an isolated 1/2<110> screw dislocation in fcc aluminum by imprinting
# the Volterra solution of elasticity theory,
#     u_z(x,y) = (b/2*pi) * atan2(y-yc, x-xc),
# on a perfect cylinder of atoms with a single displace_atoms command driven
# by an atom-style variable.  The outer shell of the cylinder is then frozen
# (it carries the correct elastic far field) and the interior is relaxed:
# the core dissociates into two Shockley partial dislocations bounding a
# ribbon of stacking fault, which is identified with common neighbor
# analysis and measured with the bound() group function.
#
# Frame: x = [-1 1 -2], y = [-1 1 1] (glide-plane normal), z = [1 1 0]
# (dislocation line and Burgers vector).  The dislocation is periodic along
# its line (boundary p in z) and the cylinder is shrink-wrapped in x and y.

# 1) Initialization
units metal
dimension 3
boundary s s p
atom_style atomic

# 2) System definition
variable a0 index 4.08165          # Zhou EAM equilibrium value (Tutorial 1)
variable R  index 30.0             # cylinder radius (Angstrom)
variable b  equal ${a0}/sqrt(2.0)  # Burgers vector |1/2<110>| = 2.886 A
lattice fcc ${a0} orient x -1 1 -2 orient y -1 1 1 orient z 1 1 0 &
        origin 0.1 0.1 0.1
region cyl cylinder z 0.0 0.0 ${R} 0 $(3*v_b) units box
create_box 1 cyl
create_atoms 1 region cyl

# 3) Settings
pair_style eam/alloy
pair_coeff * * Al_zhou.eam.alloy Al

# 4) Imprint the Volterra field of a screw dislocation along the cylinder
#    axis.  Every atom computes its own displacement from its own position;
#    the center (xc,yc) is placed off any atom row.  The atan2() branch cut
#    makes u_z jump by exactly b across the half-plane y=yc, x<xc -- which
#    is harmless, because b is a lattice vector: this multivaluedness IS the
#    dislocation.
variable xc equal 0.31
variable yc equal 0.47
variable uz atom (v_b/(2*PI))*atan2(y-v_yc,x-v_xc)
displace_atoms all move 0.0 0.0 v_uz units box

# 5) Freeze the outer shell AFTER the displacement, so it holds the elastic
#    far-field solution in place (cf. the rigid grips of Tutorial 7)
variable Rin equal ${R}-8.0
region rin cylinder z 0.0 0.0 ${Rin} INF INF units box
group core region rin
group ring subtract all core
fix hold ring setforce 0.0 0.0 0.0

# 6) Monitoring
thermo 100
thermo_style custom step pe fnorm

# 7) Relax the interior: the core dissociates into two Shockley partials
min_style cg
minimize 1.0e-10 1.0e-12 10000 100000

# 8) Identify the stacking-fault ribbon between the partials (CNA code 2 =
#    hcp coordination) and measure its extent in the glide plane.  Note the
# screw can dissociate on either of the two {111} planes that contain its
#    line; the in-plane extent below is measured plane-agnostically.
compute cna all cna/atom 3.45
run 0 post no
variable ishcp atom "c_cna == 2"
group hcp variable ishcp
variable dwid equal sqrt((bound(hcp,xmax)-bound(hcp,xmin))^2+(bound(hcp,ymax)-bound(hcp,ymin))^2)
print "--------------------------------------------------"
print "Atoms total                    = $(count(all))"
print "Stacking-fault (hcp) atoms     = $(count(hcp))"
print "Fault ribbon extent            = $(v_dwid:%.2f) Ang"
print "--------------------------------------------------"

# 9) Save the relaxed configuration for visualization
write_data screw.data
